Saturday, January 1, 1949

Started the year off by working all day and evening on rattlesnake locomotion and practically finished the first draft. It has been a slow subject.

Page Edit History:
  • Lewisia 06/06/2012 10:53 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:55 PM

Sunday, January 2, 1949

Today the section on locomotion was finally completed. Began bringing the other parts of the Behavior chapters down to date for submission to Perkins and other reviewers. Worked from early morning to late evening, except for a brief interlude taking down the Christmas tree.

Page Edit History:
  • Lewisia 06/06/2012 11:14 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:55 PM

Monday, January 3, 1949

(June 4 continued)
1 Dip AOR 10 mi. S. of Amboy, S.B Co. desert.
1 chuck on black lava 5 mi. W. of Amboy, S.B. Co. 10:00 Escaped.
1 shot dip. here at 10:05. on black lava.
1 dip. SoR Siberia SB Co. 10:22
Got 5 chuckwallas at Klondike, S.B Co.
on black lava at 10:40. Slightly overcast.
There was a male & female on one rock. Female was reddish.
Shot a whiptail and dip at Ash Hill, S.B.Co.
Also saw a chuck here. 10:50 Rocky desert with scattered brush.
Reached Ludlow at 11:00; pickled specimens and left at 11:40.
Stopped to hunt in sand dunes 1 mi. E. of Ludlow, S.B. Co. Got a chuck and 2 dips. callies, Utas, and whiptails were seen. 12:05. Had a premature explosion of my collecting pistol; fragments of shell cut my left hand at several places. Returned to Ludlow and cleaned it up. Left again at 12:17.Noted the country at Hector?? where the queer Chionactis were collected many years ago. The entire surface is almost
(continued on Jan. 4th)

Tuesday, January 4, 1949

(June 4, continued from Jan. 3)
covered with black lava and sand. There is sage and creosote; also sandy places, including dunes. Plenty of brush. It looks like good Chionactis territory.
1 Red racer M DOR. Troy S.B Co. Reddish with black neck. Brushy desert.
2 Dips SOR Rancho Larga Vega, S.B. Co. At Daggett we turned north to U.S. 91 and thence eastward again. Passed Yermo eastbound at 1:50.
1 gopher M DOR 3 mi. E. of Yermo, S.B. Co. Sandy desert, light brush. Neck spots OK for deserticola.
Got 2 chucks 3 mi. W. of Cronise??, S.B, Co.
The male bobbed; was this courting?
1 platyrhinos COR on rock 4 mi. E. of Cronise. 2:45.
chucks seen and one collected 7 mi. SW of Baker, S.B.Co. On rocks as usual.
Reached Baker at 3:20. Got gas & oil & fixed specimens. Left at 4 PM; warm.
At Silver Lake we turned over many ties of the defunct Tonopah & Tidewater Ry. Got a Coleonyx and saw a Uta stans.
1 platyrhinos COR. 7 mi. S. of Ibex Pass, S.B.Co. Scattered creosote & burro weed. Now a storm coming up. Partly overcast
1 Dip shot on the road 3 mi. S. of Ibex Pass, S.B.Co.
(continued on Jan. 5)

Wednesday, January 5, 1949

(June 4, continued from Jan 4)
It was now warm and overcast. Had some sprinkles of rain.
Ate dinner at Shoshone and left north-bound at 6:18.
Stopped to hunt 10 mi N of Shoshone. A Cally was seen at 6:45 after the sun had set. Overcast 87 degrees.
Turned around and headed southward when 20 miles north of Shoshone. 7:05 pm
Cloudy and breezy 84 degrees. Still some light.
1 Cally DOR. 11 mi N of Shoshone, Inyo Co. Rocky desert, scattered brush.
1 Sidewinder COR 11 mi. N of Shoshone, Inyo Co. 7:32, 87 degrees brushy desert. A queer individual with a sharp pointed tail and no rattles.
1 Coleonyx COR same place at 7:33
Back at Shoshone at 8:03, 86 degrees; now dark.
1 leafnose COR 2 mi S. of Shoshone, Inyo Co. 8:11 87 degrees breezy.
1 gopher L DOR saved same place.
Took the detour via Tecopa.
1 Uta stans DOR 5 mi N. of Ibex Pass (S.B. Co) but in Inyo Co.
1 Coleonyx COR 9:56 84 degrees breezy 2 mi N of Ibex Pass (S.B. Co) but in Inyo Co.
Stopped near here to change a tire
(Continued on Jan 6th)

Thursday, January 6, 1949

(June 4, continued from Jan. 5th)
Went on at 9:30.
1 Coleonyx COR Ibex Pass, S.B. Co. 9:32; 87 degrees.
1 callie DOR. 4 mi. N. of Renoville, S.B.Co.
1 Coleonyx COR. 5 mi. S. of Renoville. S.B.Co. 10:20.
1 platy DOR, 2 mi. N. of Silver Lake, S.B. Co. Arrived at Baker at 11:00. 84 degrees, breezy.
No accounting for the poor results tonight. The temperature was OK and the moon was obscured most of the time.
Miles today 347.
Miles evening drive 85; 3 hrs., 55 min.

Friday, January 1, 1949

(June 5th continued)
1 R.l.lecontei L DOR. 6 mi. W. of Yermo. Gravelly desert with brush.
1 Red racer. L DOR. 9 mi. W.of Yermo, gravelly desert with brush.
1 callie L DOR 9 mi. W. of Yermo. Gravelly desert with brush.
Stopped to hunt at Mace, S.B.Co.. got one dip on a rocky hill; saw another in the top of a creosote bush. Shot 2 cnemis in flat sandy and brushy desert. Shaw got a bat Myotus in a rock crevice
1 platyrhinos DOR. Mace, S.B.Co. Sandy, brushy desert.
1 Chionactis L DOR (saved) 2 mi. W. of Hinkley. S.B.Co. Flat sandy desert, scattered creosote and dense burro weed
1 whiptail seen on the road at 12:09. Same data as above.
1 whiptail DOR Jim Grey, San Bernardino Co., Sandy desert, creosote.
1 whiptail DOR Jim Grey, S.B.Co. Sandy desert, creosote.
1 cally DOR Jim Grey. S.B.Co., Sandy desert creosote.
1 tortoise DOR Jim Grey, S.B.Co.. Sandy desert, creosote.
1 platyrhinos DOR Jim Grey, S.B. Co. Sandy desert, creosote.
Had lunch at Boron, Kern Co.
1 whiptail DOR 2 mi. W. of Boron, Kern Co. Sandy brushy desert
1 Leopard lizard L 5 mi. W. of Boron; sandy, brushy desert.
1 leopard lizard L 14 mi. W. of Boron. Sandy, brushy desert.
1 whiptail SOR 11 mi. E. of Mojave, Kern Co.. Sandy, brushy desert.
1 Cally SOR 4 mi. E. of Mojave, Kern Co.. Sandy desert.
We arrived in Lancaster at 3 p.m. and secured a room for Shaw. We had supper
(continued on Jan.8th

Saturday, January 8, 1949

Worked all day and late into the evening incorporating the latest new data into the Frailty and Senses sections.
-----------------------------------------------------------------
(June 5th continued from Jan. 7)
I waited around and caught the northbound owl, while Shaw ran the road with the following results:
Left Lancaster at 7:07. Sun has set.
Palmdale at 7:20 brezzy 77°.
Pearblossom 7:50 77°
1 Scute DOR S (saved) 1 mi. E of Llano LA Co
1 Arizona L DOR (fresh) 10 " " " " " "
(dark; 1/2 moon).
Adelanto at 9:30 71°.
1 Chionactis DOR (saved) 5 mi. N. of Adelanto
1 coleonyx DOR " " " " "
1 gopher S DOR 9 " " " "
1 coleonyx DOR 13 " " " "
1 Platyrhinos DOR 14 " " " "
1 Chionactis DOR (saved) 16 " " " "
1 Scute L DOR 14 mi. S. of Kramer Junct
1 R. l. lecontei L DOR 13 do
2 Chinoactis DOR (saved) 11 do breezy
1 Chionactis COR 11 do 10:40; 75°
1 sidewinder COR 7 do 10:55; 69°
(Continued on Jan. 9th)

Sunday, January 9, 1949

Worked all day and evening making
further changes and additions to Senses
and Temporal Activity. The latter still unfinished.
----------------------------------------------------------------
(June 5th continued from Jan 8th)

1 Banded King LDOR(squirming; saved)5mi.S.ofKramer Junct.
1 Chionactis DOR(saved)3"""""
1 Platyrhinos DOR1"""""

Kramer Junctionat11:15;68°.TurnedW. to Mojave.
1 ChionactisDOR(saved)1mi.WofKramer Junct.
1 Arizona LDOR2"""""
1 Chionactis LDOR (saved)Kramer, S.B.Co..
1 Arizona LDOR.7mi.W.ofBoron,Kern Co
1 P. c. desrticolaCOR8""""12:00; 68°
1 PlatyrhinosDOR11""""
1 Chionactis LDOR(saved)same.
1 Leopard LDOR10mi.EofMohave
1 ChionactisDOR(saved)4""""

Reached Mojave at 1 AM. 74° Breezy
and Lancaster at 1:50 AM.

Too cold tonight for the best results; the
larger number of DOR's indicated they were
out early.

Miles today 365.
Evening drive (to Mohave only)
100 miles; 5 hours.

Wednesday, January 12, 1949

(June 7, Continued)
1 Leopard DOR 4 mi N.W. of Cajon Jnct, SBCo Rested at Colton and worked over specimens. Chaparral
1 Gopher S DOR March Field Riv Co. Grass.
1 H.T. DOR 1 mi. W of Perris. Grass & granite
1 Gopher S DOR
1 Gopher L DOR 4 mi. N. of Elsinor's height brush grass.
1 Red Racer L DOR. 4 mi SE of Murrieta fields & stream black neck.
1 Banded King S DOR Ranibow SD Co
1 Cal striped racer S DOR Pala. Chaparral.
Had another puncture and bought a new casing at Pala. Ate dinner at Lake Henshaw.
1 Gopher S DOR. Warners Ranch. Grass
1 Banded King L DOR Warners Ranch. Grass
Reached Scissors Crossing at 6:25 (??? :35??)breezy and windy. Cool. 76. Almost full moon.
Left Scissors at 6:58. Went down to bridge and back, then left for a full moon.
Second start 7:21 76 degrees windy.
1 Colevmy X COR top Sentenac above cattle guard 77 degrees 7:26.
1 Worm Snake COR Bottom Sentenac 7:36 82 degrees still light in the west.
(Continued on Jan. 13)

On the whole a very successful trip, particularly Shaw's two nights alone, when he got 18 Chionactis, the purpose of the expeditions.

Friday, January 14, 1949

Clipping from San Diego Union
Graphic shows January 3rd through January 5th "Worst Freeze in 37 yrs. "January 6 through January 8th "Nearly Normal." January 9 to January 12 "First Snow Recorded in 99 yrs." January 12 through 14th "Heavy Rain, Wind."

Caption: Here it is at a glance - the darndest January (to date) in San Diego weather history. Small figures show daily temperature deficiency. End of week could be a heat wave, for all we know.

Headline: Only Heat Wave Left as Surprise
Article: If January has any weather surprises left for San Diego it will have to be a winter heat wave, the weather bureau conceded yesterday. With the month not half gone the record showed:
First week, bright sunshine coupled with the hardest freeze in 37 years; second week, two heavy storms - one bringing the only snowfall recorded since 1850, the other deluging the area with rain and buffeting it with wind.

Saturday, January 15, 1949

Too many Company troubles to think of any herpetological work today. (Partially hidden behind clipping "The Leslie Griffins visiting us.")

Balance of newspaper clipping:
Jan. 4 failed to equal the all-time low of 24 recorded her in 1913, the first 12 days of the month were considerably colder than the comparable period 37 years ago. Dean Blake, senior meteorologist, reported.
"So far its the coldest January since the weather bureau was established in 1872," Blake said. The 12-day mean temperature through Wednesday was 46.8 degrees - 7.2 below average. The daily deficiency below normal mean totaled 87 degrees, compared with 78 in the corresponding period in January 1913. The day-by-day 1949 record:

Wednesday, March 30, 1949

Took a drive this afternoon with GG (???&???) the Whlendorfs (???). Started at 12:30 and returned at 8:30. A cool windy day; very windy in the Borrego Valley and cold; rain from Warners to Valley Center. Route El Cajon, Ramona, Julian, Banner, Yaqui Pass, Borrego Valley (drove around to see the flowers which were very fine), Scissors Crossing, Warners, Morrettis (???), Rincon (dinner here) Valley Center, Escondido home. Total miles 234. Could call it daylight to Henshaw darn. A few white spots seen after the rain began, which may have been toads.
Only one snake a Chionactis L DOR at Yaqui Pass (west side) saved.

Evening drive April 16th

Friday, April 15, 1949

Went to a Calif. State Chamber of Commerce meeting at 10 AM.; it lasted until 3:30. We got started for Palm Springs at 4 and reached there at about 6.
Started out on an evening drive at 7:30 -- too late as it was already cooling fast. Breezy; no moon.
1 Sidewinder L COR 4 mi. SE of Palm Springs 7:45 72 degrees F
1 Coleonyx L COR mouth of Berdoo Canyon 9:25
1 Sidewinder L COR Garnet 10:20 59 degrees and a gale blowing. He was able to navigate with some uncertainty, and was hard to get into the bottle.
Reached Palm Springs at 10:30 faint moon.
Warmer here with less wind.
The trip had been Palm Springs, side trip to La Quinta, Indio, Aqueduct Road, Garnet and Palm Springs. The trip was a failure because of the late start and cold. Evening drive 3 hours; 73 miles.

Sunday, April 17, 1949

Started from Victorville for Trona and Mojave at 9:35 AM. Warm and clear; little wind.
1 tortoise crossing the road 14 mi. S. of Kramer Junction and another at Kramer Hills (about 10 AM)
Uta Stans 12 mi. N. of Johannesburg.
Went to Trona and had lunch there
1 Dip DOR (saved) at Westend (Starles Lake)
1 Salvadora g. mohavensis DOR 1 mi W. of Salt Wells (n.w. corner San Bernardino Co) sandy desert.
1 Dip DOR Inyokern.
1 Red Racer M DOR. Pine Tree Station, San Bernardino Co. Creosote bush desert. Brown body; some black on the head.
Reached Mohave at 3:15.
Ran the road east of Mojave from 5:50 to 7:20. Cold and windy. 64 degrees to 61 degrees. Nothing seen. 34 miles 1 1/2 hours. The road is now too wide to be good. All brush trimmed off for about 120' width.
Caught the Owl for SF at 9:15; left car in Mojave garage.

Tuesday, April 19, 1949

Opened the bids on $6,000,000 of preferred stock. Best bid a little under par. Accepted
Went to Berkeley at noon and worked in the library most of the afternoon. Picked up a few items. Saw Stebbins, Wade Fox, and Provin. Talked over their recent collecting trips.
Caught the Owl at Berkeley at 7:20 P.M.

Saturday, April 23, 1949

Miscellaneous work today and a Rubenstein concert in the evening. Reread the color-pattern section and made some final changes. All finished with this now except the laborious job of describing individual species.
Went over to the zoo and got a lot of snakes collected by Miles in the vicinity of Hamilton Ranch, B.C.
Looked over the C. Willardi and Chionactis problems again to see just how they stand. Brought some tables down to date.

Thursday, May 5, 1949

Drove down from Long Beach this morning.
Saw at the zoo a DOR Tantilla collected at Boquet Canyon 14 mi. N of Newhall, L.A. Co by Bud Hathcock.

Ridgway colors of a Scink (rubricandatus) from Black Rock springs, N.W. Joshua Tree National Monument, about 5000 ft elev. Lloyd Mason Smith.
Tail Peach Red
Ventrum Light Niagara Green
Lower edges of head Ochra ceous slamon
Black dorsal stripes between Dusky Violet Blue and Black
Interspaces between dark dorsal stripes Ivory Yellow.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(May 6th, concluded)
Reached Blythe again at 11 P.M. and turned in. Our failure to get specimens in Arizona was no doubt due to low temperature, probably not above 74 degrees at any time, and mostly below.
Total miles today 304.
Miles evening drive (counting only pavement, and omitting Quartzite - Blyth a/c high speed: 66; time 2 hrs, 45 min.

Friday, May 6, 1949

Started for the desert today with Chuck Shaw. 1:10 P.M. Clear and hot.
1 Rhinocheilus L. DOR Mission Gorge grass fields
1 Salvadora M DOR Buckman Spr. light brush

Jacumba at 2:54 clear and cool

Reached Yuma t 6:55 MST and had supper.
Then started north for Quartzsite.
1 Gopher L DOR 2 mi. E of Yuma.
There is first 10 miles of cultivated Gila Valley, after which one climbs to a sort of desert mesa. The country looks good but we had no luck.
1 Cnemidophorus DOR 4 mi. W. of Dome Yuma Co
1 P.p.platyrhinos DOR (saved) 15 mi No of Dome Yuma Co
The pavement ends 33 mi. N. of Yuma, so there are 23 miles of desert pavement. Sunset at 7:23; still faint light to the west at 8:10
1 Sidewinder M COR. 18 mi S. of Quartzsite, Yuma Co 9:10 68 degrees
1 Chionactis L DOr 9 mi S. of Quartzsite, Yuma Co
Reached the junction with 60-70 at 9:50, 70 degrees F
There were 29 miles of finished paving S. of Quartzite
Reached Blythe at 9:40 P.S.T. 1/2 moon, quiet & cool, 62 degrees.
Ran up the road toward Midland for 9 miles. Got 3 Bufo cognatus 2 mi. N. of Blythe.

Monday, May 16, 1949

(May 27th)
Philip and I took a trip to Arizona and Sonora. Started at 5:35 P.M. Cool and overcast.
1 Gopher M DOR Flinn Springs. Grass. Dusk at Pine Valley. Count only 48 miles in S.D. Co as daylight drive.
1 Chionactis COR (but injured) Mt. Springs Grade 2 mi. E. of SD Co line. 7:35 PM 78 degrees F Rocky gorge.
Reached Coyote Wells at 7:45. Had a blowout just beyond. A tough place and a violent gale blowing. Unlatched the top of the baggage compartment and dropped it on Phil's head, fortunately not a great drop.
1 Chionactis DOR (squirming) 1 mi. W of Dixieland. Saved
1 Rhioncheilus l. lecontei DOR saved 1 mi S. of Selley.
1 T. maricianus DOR 4 mi. W. of Calexico Irrigation ditch
1 P.c.affinis COR S 4 mi. E Calexico 9:34 81 degrees F fields
1 S.s.linearis L DOR. 3 mi. W. of Bond's Corner saved
1 Coleonyx SOR. 10 mi. E of Bond's Corner 79 degrees
1 Cerastes S COR 2 mi. W. of Midway Well 79 degrees 10:05
1 Phyllorhynchus L DOR (squirming) 8 mi. W. of Ariz a particularly large specimen 460-63c
Reached Yuma at 11:20 PST and put up at the Coloma Auto Court. It was then quite cold. Drove fast part of the way.
Count the evening drive 80 miles; 3 hours.
Miles today 184 (??? or 84)

Tuesday, May 17, 1949

(May 28th)
Started east from Yuma at 9:40 MST.
1 Arizona M DOR. 1 mi. W. of Wellton. Grassy desert saved
1 Red racer M DoR 2 mi. W. of Dateland, Yuma Co saved.
Passed Sentinel at 11:25. Hot. No lizards to seen.
1 Cerastes L. DOR Theba, Maricopa Co brushy desert.
1 Dip DOR. 8 1/2 N. of Ajo, Pima Co.
Reached Ajo at at 1 PM. Quite hot. Not a live lizard had been seen all morning.
1 (?) Whiptail SOR. 5 mi. S. of Ajo, Pima Co 1:40 P.M.
1 Whiptail SOR. 9 mi. S. of Ajo, Pima Co
Reached the US Boundary at 2:30 and Sonoyta at 2:55. Here we took a room at the hotel and then went on (???senth??? something wrong with scan, can't enlarge???) From here the country is mixed desert creosote, mesquite, sahuaros. Some rocky stretches; getting increasingly sandy toward the south west; some sand dunes scattered about. Ocotillo. Some quite barren stretches. Reached Punto Penasco early in the afternoon and killed time looking about. Had dinner.
Left Punto Penasco at 7:30. just sunset.
at 8 P.M. it was not yet dark. 81 degrees F.
1 Chionactis S COR 4 mi. SW of El Papalote 8:14 77 degrees F. grassy desert. Not quite dark.
1 Chionactis L DOR. 1 mi. SW of El Papalote saved.
1 Coleonyk COR. 1 mi. NE of El Papalote 81 degrees 8:35 P.M.
(Continued on May 18th)

Thursday, May 19, 1949

(Entry for May 29th)
Started north from Sonoyta at 8:25 MST.
Part cloudy, sultry, warm.
Whiptail and Uta ornata seen 1 mi. N. of Sonoyta.
Stopped at the Headquarters of the Organpipe Cactus National Monument and saw Supernaugh's (???) and Max Hensley's collections of snakes, including some very interesting Chionactis some of which are like palarostris and some not. Hensley was not there. Borrowed Supernaugh's (???) specimen but not Hensley's. The monument headquarters is 7 miles north of the International Boundary.
Went 5 mi. beyond the headquarters and discovered one large forceps had been left.
On the way back, 5 mi. N. of headquarters, there was a red racer on the road with his head raised well off the ground in the usual way. Chased him into a mesquite and thought we had lost him but finally located him stretched out among the limbs 7' above ground. Grabbed him and got bitten as usual. This was at 10:15 AM.
1 Atrox DOR 6 mi. N. of headquarters. Mesquite desert. Quite red.
(Continued on May 20)

Friday, May 20, 1949

(May 29 continued from May 19)
1 Whiptail SOR gunsight (???) Pima Co.
Worried about gas supply o/c (???) stores through the Indian Reservation closed for Sunday.
Finally got some at Covered Wells.
1 Black racer L DOR 5 mi. NW of Sells, Pima Co.
Mesquite desert. All black. Saved head.
1 Racer ? San Vicente, Pima Co. Bones picked clean. Couldn't identify.
Arrived at Tuscon at 1:30. Hot and windy.
Had lunch and started for Nogales at 2:15 most of the morning it had been cool and overcast, yet no lizards (or only 1) had been seen, showing it is not the neat that keeps them out of sight in the late morning.
Saw Earl Jackson at Tumacacaori NM. and talked snakes with him. He had a tantilla and a coral snake among others.
Took a room at the El Portal Lodge at Nogales and started south at 5:15. Cloudy and somewhat cool.
South of the line the country is quite different from north. Much of the trip to Santa Ana and below is a long a river valley. It does not look like particularly good snake country, except for the occasional stretches across mesas.
(Continued on May 21)

Saturday, May 21, 1949

(May 29 continued from May 20)
Where there is mesquite, sahuaros, and cactus.
1 Phrynosoma colare COR 7 mi. NE of Magdalena 6:35
1 Helodernice suspectum COR (injured) ditto.
We ate supper at 7:30 and turned around this was 4 mi. S. of Llano = 17 mi. S. of Santa Ana = 83 mi. S. of the border.
Started back north at 7:50; still light in the west.
1 Hypsiglena to o chroohynchus (???) COR 5 mi. NE of Magdalena. 9:03; 84 degrees.
Arrived at Nogales at 11:05. 81 degrees new moon; breezy, but slight only.
Evening drive 84 mi. 3 1/4 hrs. Miles today 391.
An exceedingly disappointing evening. Only 1 snake and not a coleonyx. No chionactis. We drove slowly and didn't miss anything. The road was fairly clean. The temperature was ok. So it must have been the wrong season (some say after the first rains is the time) or it is just poor snake country.
We had failed to get our visitors permits at Nogales and had a disturbing time at the Inspection Station at Casita. $5.00 finally fixed it.

Tuesday, May 31, 1949

(May 30th continued)
wide as in a S.D. Co specimen.
There is a sandy wash across the SP tracks which may account for the chionactis here.
1 Whiptail SOR. Piedra, Maricopa Co
1 Red racer L DOR brown head. Winterhaven River bottom.
1 Arizona very large DOR 2 mi. W. of Winterhaven desert one side; fields on other
1 R.l.lecontei L DOR Fields 2 mi. E of Meloland (typical lecontei; no clarus)
1 same 1 mi. W. of Meloland.
1 Gopher L. DOR (??? Suley ???) fields.
1 Gopher L DOR Live Oak Spring fields.
Reached home at 7:20 Cold.
Miles today 515
Miles for the trip 1422
Today was another example of the parcity of lizards even when it is not too hot for them. For it was cool and overcast almost all of the way from Tucson to Mountains Spring. Note also the prevalence of DOR's in cultivated territory compared with the desert. Shows it would pay to get drive yourself cars and not make such lonely trips to pick up material on the road.

N Sunday, June 5, 1949

This morning we left Baker at 7:51. First going eastward on US91
1 Gopher L. DOR. 2 mi. W of Yucca Grove, S.B.Co; brushy desert with tree yuccas. Although this snake was flattened and stuck to the pavement, when we returned about 1/2 hour later, 2 buzzards had pulled it loose from the pavement and were trying to get what they could out of it.
Got 3 Xantusia vigilis under dead yucca stems at Yucca Grove, SB Co
1 Red Racer M DOR. 14 mi. W. of Baker, SB Co. black neck; rocky desert with scattered creosote bush.

Monday, June 6, 1949

I arrived in SF at 8:50 and spent the morning and afternoon until 2:30 with Fox and Wehe. We had an interview with the Commission engineers from 9:30 to 1 PM. Went over to Berkeley at 4 and saw Stebbins and Fox. Looked at their specimens of L. pyromelana. Left on the Owl at 7:20. The rest of the entry comprises Shaw's adventures.
Left Lancaster at 9:35 AM. Warm and partly overcast.

Tuesday, June 1, 1949

I arrived this morning at Lancaster at 6:32 on the Owl.
Shaw was late in meeting me as he had been up late last night and was sick besides. We took our time getting started. I made color notes on the DOR chionactis that had been put in the refrigerator the night before.
We finally left Lancaster at 8:37. It was clear and warm.
1 Banded King S DOR. 2 mi. S. of Lancaster sandy desert

Tuesday, June 14, 1949

Went to Los Angeles this morning at 8 and served on a board of 5 to interview candidates for asst. chief electrical engineer of the Bureau of Water & Power of LA. The other members of the board were Dr Bridge and Sorenson of Cal. Tech., Coons of Occidental and Moulton of PG&E. An interesting experience. Returned on the 7:30 train.

Thursday, June 16, 1949

Drove home from Pine Hills this morning. Started at 8 and arrived at 9:40 Cloudy and cool. Did not stop for DORs of which at least 4 fresh ones were seen.

Received a telegram today that T had been elected President of the Pacific Division of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.

Sunday, June 26, 1949

Went down to the express office first thing this morning and got 2 live specimens of Chionactis palarostris sent by Supernaugh of Organ Pipe Cactus National Monument. Then went to the zoo and got Perkin's and Shaw's suggestions on the C. Willardi paper. Also got a lot of specimens. Met Col. O.L. Miles who collected in lower California and Florida.
Spent the afternoon on Chionactus. Noted that the specimens of palarostris have blunter and more convex snouts than occipitalis. Evidently they are different species. I had noted this when describing palarostris but had forgotten it.
Also did a lot of work arranging containers in the basement.

Sunday, July 10, 1949

Today went to the Old Timer's Barbecue at Fenton's Ranch, San Pasqual. Started at 10:30 and returned at 3:15. Had a good time and a good lunch, although it was tiring standing in line so long. Saw a lot of people I hadn't seen in years.
Before and after, and late into the evening did bibliographic work on the rattle and made good progress.

Spent the time 11 to 4 at the O.C. Library in Berkeley. Saw Wade Fox and the data on a Borrego specimen of Chionactis belonging to Glaser.

At the SF Public Library from 6:30 to 7:30; and at Stanford Medical Library from 7:50 to 8:30.
On the whole it was a poor day. Few bibliographic uncertainties were cleared up.

Saturday, August 13, 1949

In the morning worked on the completed section on the rattle, incorporating new material. Finished this part totalling 200 hand-written pages.
At noon went to a small lunch for secy of the Navy Mathews.
Spent the afternoon and evening making a start on the statistical section on the rattle. This will require a lot of statistical computations to incorporate importatn new materia.

Page Edit History:
  • nwyld 03/13/2013 10:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:55 PM

Sunday, August 14, 1949

Spent the entire day and evening bringing the rattle statistics to date by adding all the measurements accumulated since 1934 when the first draft of the statistical paper was written. This is a big job and will take a lot of time, but it will certainly make the conclusions more valid. Hate to take the time for this but don't see how it is to be avoided.

Monday, September 5, 1949

Left Fallen Leaf at 9:30 A.M. Stopped at Minden and called on the Dangberg's who own father's old ranch which is still known as the "Klauber Ranch." Then went out to the ranch and talked with the present tenant; also took some pictures. A part of the old adobe milk-house is still to be seen, but the chronology of the ranch house itself is still somewhat doubtful.
At lunch at Gardnerville.

1 Whiptail SOR Topaz Lake

Arrived at Bishop at 4:45. Stopped at the Sierra Motel. Town hot, and crowded o/c (???) of rodeo.
Started the evening drive up US6 at 6:40 Dusk, full moon, warm.
2 Scaphiopus intermontanus COR 14 mi S. of Benton, Mono Co. 7:30

Tuesday, September 6, 1949

Started for home this morning at 7:30.
Clean and warm.
1 Red Racer S DOR a4 mi. N. of Independence sagebrush desert saved.
1 Red Racer L DOR 6 mi. S. of Independence Fields
Went around the east side of Owens Lake via Keller to see the old Cerro Gordo tramway. Unfortunately had used up all the films.
1 Red Racer L DOR 2 mi. S. of Little Lake.
Creosote brush desert. Plenty black on neck.
Whiptails crossing the road 2 mi. N of Adelanto.
It was very hot all afternoon. Ate lunch at San Bernardion.
Arrived home at 5:00.
Miles in the county 55. Miles today 377.
Total miles for the trip 1463.

While I travelled fast on this trip I doubt whether many snakes, if any, were overlooked. The fall is nothing like spring. Even in rocky areas such as around Little Lake. Only 1 or 2 lizards were seen, whereas in spring they are exceedingly plentiful.

Friday, September 23, 1949

Arrived at Sacramento at 8:30 AM. Then started for the Feather River power projects with Norman Sutherland of PG&E and Harold Quinton of Southern California Edison. We went via Marysville, Oroville and Jarboe Pass. Stopped at the Cresta and Rock Creek Power Houses now under construction. Also at the Back's Creek Power House in operations. Had a fine lunch. Went 1 1/2 mi. into one of the tunnels (diam 25') from the Jackass Creek adit. A very interesting tour.
Went on up to Caribou Power Station and camp where we had an excellent dinner, followed by our meeting.

Thursday, October 6, 1949

Received the first copies of the willardi paper today.

Left for Stanford on the 3:45 train this afternoon.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
(Oct. 7 Continued)
We went to a reception at the Presidents House (with the Myers') then to dinner at the Union. After dinner we had a bull session at the museum with Jay Savage and others; then down to Palo Alto to catch the Lark.
A full and interesting day with many experiences new to me and therefore worth the trip.
I was intrigued by the way the robes are handled by a commercial organization specializing in the business. Seems to be efficient and accurate. Almost no one, even in academic circles, seems to own a robe.

Page Edit History:
  • nwyld 03/16/2013 10:11 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:55 PM

Friday, October 7, 1949

Spent the day at Stanford attending the inauguration of Wallace Sterling as president.
Margaret Storey met me at the train. First went to the museum and then to the Library. Worked at the Library until 10:30, but got few items cleared up. Then Margaret took me through the Hoover Library tower. As she had entree to everything we saw many interesting items. Then had lunch with Bolin and Twitty. After lunch went over to the Little Theatre; where robes were donned. Then we went on the academic parade, first to services at the Chapel; then back to the Frost Amphitheatre, where speeches were made by Paul Edwards & Sterling. The various robes were most colorful and interesting, but it would take an official from the College of Heralds to interpret them. Met a number of interesting people. I participated as a member of the faculty, not a representative of an outside organization. After leaving our robes at the theatre
(Continued on Oct. 6th)

Saturday, December 31, 1949

In bed with a cold all day. Pasted book-plates in the newly bound books, otherwise practically nothing accomplished.
Didn't accomplish much last year. Spent too much time in the field in the spring because of Chionactis.
The year saw the completion of the taxonomic section of the Chionactis paper; the field notes remain to be done.
The Willardi paper was completed and published.
As to the rattler book, the final touches were put on Section 7, bodily functions; and a good start was made on Section 9, morphology.
Complete
Body proportions
Scutellation
Color and pattern
Rattles
Freaks and aberrants
Not begun
Size and weight
Skeleton
Anatomy and internal organs

California King snake

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
